Here's an example of a cute and convincing internet speedtest app that automatically loads on open and displays the current speed varying a bit, giving the result in Mbps after 10 seconds of test. It does not make a real connection speed test, but instead displays a high random number. If the URL query parameter "speed" is given, it will be used as the final result.
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
        <title>Internet Speed Test</title>
        <style>
                body {
                        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
                        background-color: #f2f2f2;
                        text-align: center;
                        padding-top: 50px;
                }

                h1 {
                        font-size: 36px;
                        color: #333;
                        margin-bottom: 20px;
                }

                p {
                        font-size: 24px;
                        color: #666;
                        margin-bottom: 10px;
                }

                #result {
                        font-size: 48px;
                        color: #00aaff;
                        margin-bottom: 20px;
                }
        </style>
</head>
<body>
        <h1>Internet Speed Test</h1>
        <p>Your download speed is:</p>
        <div id="result">Loading...</div>
        <script>
                var urlParams = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search);
                var speed = urlParams.get('speed');
                if (speed === null) {
                        speed = Math.floor(Math.random() * 500) + 100; // Generate a random number between 100 and 600 Mbps
                }
                var result = document.getElementById("result");
                result.innerHTML = speed + " Mbps";
                setTimeout(function() {
                        for (var i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
                                var variation = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10) - 5; // Generate a random variation between -5 and 5 Mbps
                                speed += variation;
                                if (speed < 100) {
                                        speed = 100; // Set minimum speed to 100 Mbps
                                } else if (speed > 600) {
                                        speed = 600; // Set maximum speed to 600 Mbps
                                }
                                result.innerHTML = speed + " Mbps";
                                setTimeout(function() {
                                        if (i === 9) {
                                                result.innerHTML = speed + " Mbps";
                                        }
                                }, (i + 1) * 1000);
                        }
                }, 10000); // Wait for 10 seconds before displaying the final result
        </script>
</body>
</html>
```

Copy and paste this code into a new HTML file, save it, and open it in your browser to see how it works. You can also modify the CSS styles and JavaScript code to customize the appearance and behavior of the app according to your needs.
